Rating: 3
Great flavor and perfect accompaniment for the Shrimp & Peppers in Spicy Tomato Sauce. As a reviewer suggested I used half low-sodium chicken broth with the water. If I were to change anything it would be to reduce the size of the cinnamon stick a little. It is amazing how much the cinnamon flavor comes through.

Rating: 3
This is quick, easy and delicious. I made this to go with a traditional Indian chicken curry, and it was a great substitute for my usual and much more time-consuming rice recipe. I will definately be making this again. I substituted a can of chicken broth plus enough water to equal the amount called for in the recipe, and cut the salt to a scant half teaspoon. In fact, you could probably totally leave out the salt. A great side dish for the time pressed cook.

Rating: 4
This is a very tasty rice dish. I used 2 cups of chicken broth to one cup of rice - left other proportions the same. Microwave for approx 15 - 20 min (depending on your microwave) -Let rest -- Perfect rice everytime.

Rating: 4
This was fantastic. It was also very easy and very quick, perfect as a side for an impressive mid-week meal.

Rating: 4
Okay kids. Seriously kickass rice here. I made it to go with the pork tenderloin medallions and pears with port mustard sauce also on this site. I get jacked when I can use cinnamon in savory dishes, and its inclusion here is inspired. I rarely give four stars for anything, but this one was right up my alley. If you don't like cinnamon in savory dishes (unadventurous), mustard (mom's boy/girl), or good taste (enlarged adenoids), take a pass on this. Otherwise, get in there. Only downside was getting the wine right with the pork dish I served alongside this. There were alot of flavors going on and my little California chardonnay never had a chance. My changes? DOUBLE the mustard seeds. That's it. E-mail me if you have a better wine choice... Oh yeah, mangoes in lime juice with a little honey for dessert. God I love food.

Rating: 3
Delicious! Much more special than plain rice. I was surprised how much the cinnamon came through. I prepared this recipe slightly differently; I popped the mustard seeds in 1 1/2 T. hot oil, and then sauteed the rice until pale gold, before adding the rest of the ingredients -- butter or ghee would be fine too. (P.S. I used a 2 qt. saute pan because everything else was occupied; no problem).

Rating: 2
This is an interesting rice recipe; a nice change of pace from plain rice.